{[show S]Partner has announced a big fit along with a short suit, and a fat point-count tempts opener toward slam. The real test is whether those points are working or sitting opposite partner's shortness.
[BID 1S] ⟦You open 1\S, showing five or more spades and opening values.⟧ Your partner splinters to 4\H, showing four-plus spade support and a singleton or void in \H with game-forcing values.
[BID 4S] ⟦A hand that looks like a slam try can be an illusion when your honors face partner's shortness, since they cash nothing extra; treat it as a minimum and sign off. You bid 4\S.⟧
[show NS]South's sixteen points look like slam material, but \HAKQJ sit directly opposite North's heart splinter, so all that strength is duplicated and the hand really plays as a minimum. That is why 4\S, not a slam try, was the winning call. It took eleven tricks, with slam off.}
