{[show S]South opens a major and North jumps in to show a big fit and a short suit. Opener has a powerful hand and dreams of slam, but the controls have to be checked before committing past game.
[BID 1H] ⟦You open one heart, showing five or more hearts and opening values. A strong opener naturally starts dreaming of slam once a big fit is announced.⟧ North splinters, the double jump third four-plus hearts, game-forcing values, and a singleton or void in diamonds. The short suit tells opener exactly where partner's shortage lies.
[BID 4N] ⟦You bid four notrump, Roman Key Card Blackwood for hearts, asking how many of the five keycards partner holds. Even with high hopes, opener checks the keycard count before pushing toward six.⟧ The reply third one or four keycards. Reading the strength shown, opener knows it is one, which leaves the partnership well short of slam-safe.
[BID 5H] ⟦You sign off in five hearts. The answer revealed two keycards missing — including the trump ace — so six hearts is simply too high, and even a strong hand must have the discipline to stop.⟧
