{[show S]South opens a major and North jumps in to show a big fit, game values, and a short suit. Opener wants to check for slam, but how far is it safe to go once the controls come back?
[BID 1H] ⟦You open one heart, promising five or more hearts and opening values. A strong major with slam potential is exactly the hand that wants to listen for a fit.⟧ North splinters, the double jump third four-plus hearts, game-forcing values, and a singleton or void in diamonds. Naming the short suit lets opener weigh whether the hands fit for slam.
[BID 4N] ⟦You bid four notrump, Roman Key Card Blackwood for hearts, asking how many of the five keycards partner holds. With trumps agreed, a keycard count tells opener whether twelve tricks are within reach.⟧ The answer third one or four keycards. From the values already shown opener can tell it is one, which leaves the partnership short of the full set.
[BID 5H] ⟦You stop in five hearts. The reply revealed that two keycards are missing between the hands, so slam would need both to fall into place — too much to gamble, and the disciplined call is to settle in five.⟧
[show NS]South held \S4 \HA9743 \DAK4 \CKJ42. The splinter showed diamond shortness and a fine heart fit, so slam beckoned. But the keycard reply revealed only three of the five keycards were present — the spade ace and the club ace were both off. With two keycards missing there was no safe slam, so South wisely settled in five hearts, which brought home eleven tricks.}
