{[show S]After opener's major, partner makes a big jump raise that announces a fit, a short suit, and game-going values. Opener now decides whether the partnership has enough control to commit to slam.
[BID 1S] ⟦You open one spade, showing five or more spades and opening values. This names the trump suit so partner can show fit and shortness in a single jump.⟧ This splinter agrees spades with four or more trumps and shows a singleton or void in hearts, plus game-forcing values. Naming the short suit lets opener judge whether the side honors are working.
[BID 4N] ⟦You launch Roman Key Card Blackwood, four notrump for spades, asking how many of the five keycards partner holds. You have the values to drive toward slam once the fit is this good.⟧ Your partner replies five clubs, showing one or four keycards. With opener already holding the bulk of the strength, one keycard is the natural reading.
[BID 5D] ⟦You bid five diamonds, a grand-slam check rather than a sign-off. Knowing the partnership has all the aces wanted, you ask about kings next.⟧ Your partner shows the spade queen but no outside king. The partnership has the trump queen yet no extra king to set up a thirteenth trick.
[BID 6S] ⟦With no grand available, you place the contract in six spades, the slam the keycards and trump queen support.⟧
[show NS]South opened a five-card spade suit with \HAKQT and \CAT9. North's four-heart splinter agreed spades and showed heart shortness, which meant South's heart honors were not wasted opposite a void or singleton but could be ruffed and cashed with the long spades. The Blackwood sequence confirmed the keycards and trump queen but no extra king, so six spades was the limit. South was off the diamond ace, but the diamond singleton ruffed that loser away; with the heart and club tops all pulling their weight, six spades brought home twelve tricks.}
[Note "1:Splinter"]
