{[show S]Partner has leapt in to show a big fit and a short suit, leaving opener to decide between game and slam. A big point-count can still be a minimum if the points sit wrong.
[BID 1H] ⟦You open 1\H, showing five or more hearts and opening values.⟧ Your partner splinters to 4\D, showing four-plus trumps for opener's hearts and a singleton or void in \D with game-forcing values.
[BID 4H] ⟦You re-count the hand. When a whole suitful of honors faces partner's shortness, those cards are dead — discount them and settle for game even with a flashy total. sign off in 4\H.⟧
[show NS]South held fifteen high-card points, but the entire \DKQJ72 lay opposite North's diamond splinter, so the diamond honors were worthless — in truth a minimum. Discounting them and bidding only 4\H was the disciplined call: the contract made exactly ten tricks, and slam was off.}
[Note "1:Splinter"]
