{[show S]Partner's jump raise pinpoints exactly where the short suit lies, and that single piece of information can be worth its weight in gold. The question is how high the partnership can count its way to once the controls and a source of extra tricks all check in.
[BID 1S] ⟦You open one spade and show at least five spades with opening values, asking partner to describe the hand.⟧ This double jump is a splinter. Your partner promises four or more spades, game-forcing values, and a singleton or void in clubs, pinpointing the short suit while agreeing the trump fit.
[BID 4D] ⟦You cue a diamond control below game, showing the ace or king of diamonds and signaling slam interest now that the spade fit is found.⟧ Your partner launches Roman Key Card Blackwood for spades, asking how many of the five keycards — the four aces and the spade king — partner holds.
[BID 5D] ⟦You answer zero or three keycards; opposite the strength already shown, that reads as three.⟧ With every keycard located, your partner bids five spades, leaving room to confirm the trump queen and a thirteenth winner before the grand.
[BID 6S] ⟦You confirm the values are all present and raise toward slam, inviting partner to count to thirteen tricks.⟧ Knowing the keycards, the trump queen, and a countable extra trick are all accounted for, your partner bids the grand slam in spades.
[BID Pass] ⟦You pass; 7\S is the final contract.⟧
[show NS]South held \SAJ743 \H3 \DA765 \C A73. The splinter announced four-plus spades and the singleton club, so South knew that lone club could be ruffed in the long-trump hand and would never cost a trick. Blackwood confirmed all the keycards, and the follow-up located the spade queen. Counting tricks: five trump tricks, the long heart suit running for several winners, the \DA, and the club ruff together come to thirteen — the grand makes by force, and it brought home all 13. The lesson: when a splinter shows useful shortness and the controls all check in, you can bid seven with confidence rather than hope.}
[Note "1:Splinter"]
[Note "2:Cue bid, a !D stopper"]
[Note "3:Blackwood 1430, for !S"]
[Note "4:A=0/5 or 3/5"]
