{[show S]A short suit dropping opposite partner's strength can turn a good hand into something far bigger. Follow how the auction nails down the controls, the trump queen, and a side king, and see how high the partnership can count its tricks.
[BID 1S] ⟦You open one spade and show at least five spades with opening values, asking partner to describe the hand.⟧ This double jump is a splinter. Your partner promises four or more spades, game-forcing values, and a singleton or void in hearts, agreeing the trump fit while pinpointing the short suit.
[BID 4N] ⟦You launch Roman Key Card Blackwood for spades, asking how many of the five keycards — the four aces and the spade king — partner holds.⟧ Your partner answers one or four keycards; given the values already shown, that reads as one.
[BID 5D] ⟦You ask for more, probing for the trump queen and side kings to see whether the grand is safe.⟧ Your partner shows the spade queen and the club king, the precise cards that secure the trump suit and supply an extra trick.
[BID 7S] ⟦With all the keycards, the trump queen, and the club king now confirmed, you bid the grand slam in spades.⟧
[show NS]South held \SAK652 \HAKT5 \DA \C975. The heart splinter showed the singleton heart sitting opposite South's \HAKT5, so a heart can be ruffed in the long-trump hand for an extra trick. Blackwood and the queen-and-king check confirmed the missing keycard, the spade queen, and the club king. Counting tricks: five trump tricks, the three club tops, the \DA, and a heart ruff come to thirteen — the grand is cold, and it brought home all 13. The lesson: once a splinter pinpoints useful shortness and the controls all check in, counting to thirteen lets you bid seven by force.}
